# Vercel Speed Insights Configuration

## Summary
Configured Vercel Speed Insights for the Next.js ticket-app project by correcting the placement of the SpeedInsights component according to the latest official documentation.

## Changes Made

### Modified Files:
- **src/app/layout.tsx** - Moved the `<SpeedInsights />` component to the correct position inside the `<body>` tag

## Implementation Details

The project already had the `@vercel/speed-insights` package installed (v2.0.0) and the component imported. However, the component was incorrectly placed before the `<body>` tag instead of inside it.

According to the official Vercel Speed Insights documentation (https://vercel.com/docs/speed-insights/quickstart), for Next.js 13.5+, the SpeedInsights component should be placed inside the body tag:

```tsx
<body>
  {children}
  <SpeedInsights />
</body>
```

This placement ensures that Speed Insights can properly track performance metrics without interfering with the page rendering.

## Verification

- ✅ Build completed successfully with no errors
- ✅ Tests run successfully (2 pre-existing test failures unrelated to this change)
- ✅ SpeedInsights component is now properly positioned inside the body tag
- ✅ All dependencies are up to date (no changes needed to package.json or lockfile)

## Next Steps

After deployment to Vercel:
1. Enable Speed Insights in the Vercel dashboard for this project
2. Monitor the Speed Insights dashboard after deployment and user visits
3. The tracking script will automatically collect performance metrics

The implementation follows the framework-specific instructions for Next.js from the official Vercel documentation.
